Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides a small nursery with all its own at such facilities: colour walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the sons of the employees of Arch.Design can visit her.
The architectonic project company Arch.Design, whose study resulted from numerous known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the building Avriopoint to include a space for its mini-guard.
The company works around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Designs its workers in the framework of their social program.
Constructors and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with child care.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Design's own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a total of over 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guard for three years with its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the request for funding contributed to the company Economy Rating.
The attention of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care, and the day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day care is provided by a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education.
Since it is a "ministery", it can only accommodate at the same time a maximum of five children, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The functioning of the day-care facility is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care facility, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guard programme are comparable to the regular pre-school curriculum.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is located among the sign companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Batlló House, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals named it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that reminds the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the sequence of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, there is a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpent and the torsion of forms continues to surprise us also inside it.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the bars, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
La Casa Batlló, located in the neighborhood of Eixample in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the previous building and starting from zero, but soon he accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated in the design of the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
In fact, decorations for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade emerged in their design.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Mila House and the Güell Park of Gaudí, in which other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the premises shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows began to call it "the house of the woods".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not at all respect the construction rules of the moment and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impressed by the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, but on the contrary: only fifteen days after the City Hall request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without any problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and sloth.
The game with both colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which instead absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of the tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entering other Gaudí buildings in the city.
