Sports and law fraud
Bullshits like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax show genius but not willingness to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the party disputed on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether or not such behaviour is anti-sport and if, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As it is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when taking away errors to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of its group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction of the next party of the Liquilla, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned the team coach José Mourinho with two parties and various economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been played by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem assumes nobility and honor, and that it has sometimes fined its players by similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently by Mourinho, who adds a more episode to its dilated history of hystrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether such conduct is not expressly prohibited by the rules of procedure contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are a crime of law; because, in fact, they are actions that are respectful of the sport rules, but they seem to circumvent their meaning.
The issue goes on to examine the type of damage that causes the sports spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposite players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to by the clean game is to prevent the team of the players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradoxical thing about the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not fit what we normally characterized as a trap or a law fraud, because its violation of the rules was not hidden in order to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action sought to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the arbitrator.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage are obtained by the offenders in the alleged shortcomings examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not in a disadvantaged position and that the same party has no benefit, since the result of the action is obviously to leave the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club can't count on these players.
The advantage, of course, is that the players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the equipment can be eliminated at the first exchange, and with this action players perform a sanction party and pass to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards takes place with less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sport spirit, from which it is part of making strategic decisions that favor the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In the present case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without drawing the punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between intelligence and law fraud is widespread, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises by two factors: because it was about two self-expulsiones and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
