A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the UN has proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) in a quantity that corresponds to almost one third of the additional decrease to be carried out to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is framed in the set of major concrete projects that the United Nations expects to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70 per cent of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by light bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, large issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that had to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, still 5 Gt of this quantity should be reduced to stabilize, by 2020, the two-degree temperature increase to prevent it from being out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact light bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED light bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced by twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those released by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit very little heat.
Above all, they contain nothing of mercury.
Several experts have expressed their reservations regarding fluocompact light bulbs, since they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact bulbs, but the coal thermal plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is poured down with the incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billions of dollars per year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
