Hackers revengers and diligent spies
WikiLeaks has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that just seems to be scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound international changes and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is to confirm that each file created by a secret service (irrespective of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The norm that secret files should only be made up of public knowledge news is essential for the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Temples or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for new things about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust in what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the chief of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), which only considers certain what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that sent the US embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as the newsweek published last week.
Why, then, have such a revolt caused the revelations of these files?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can be called by telephone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly well, we just seem to know that we don't know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker could consult the most powerful secrets of the country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both victims and "verdugues".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
In ancient times, in Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The prophecy of Orwell has come true since, being able to control each movement thanks to the phone, each transaction performed, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a full victim of the power eye.
But when it is demonstrated, as now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the revenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets be sustained?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has not harmed Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put on the grid any information reserved, since it would be like publishing it on a road sign.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has moved on a plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain in the future private and confidential relations?
I know perfectly well that for the time being, my prediction is science fiction and, therefore, new, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the spying attempt of the Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized the communications, the Internet has re-created a cable telegraph (telephones).
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and going back, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now CDs (digitals) only allow to advance or back from chapter to chapter, that is, to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while on the plane, with the displacements it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing other than normal that communication policies and techniques bring us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was being planned in secret at the embassies.
It is currently the embassies who ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's hats in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked funding promises (called fast start or early start) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to provide EUR 7.2 billion in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society wanted all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without damaging official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has made reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years of fast start funding is added.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro lent is equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to reducing emissions based on more effective technologies), it is false to present a euro that is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... As a matter of fact, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of a interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respect" its commitment of EUR 420 million making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it through its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union makes a euro to meet its commitment, France only gives ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast-start funding, France does double-use: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it can give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to donate when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a short-term, short-term detail in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other European Union countries.
But, in particular, France could move forward the discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
We therefore hope for the new Minister of Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast-starting and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
Warning on child-ingested pesticides
A 10-year-old boy eats on one day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published on Wednesday by the Association Generations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are an illustration of the problem treated," acquired food from Oise and Paris supermarkets between July and September that usually consumes a child about ten years of age in four meals and a daily snack.
These foods taken as a model, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of milk products and 1.5 litres of water per day), as well as the golosins, were examined in the laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although almost all of the cases do not exceed the legal limits for each of the chemicals individually, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is worrying," the association points out.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a tentempie for the school, contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to the green Jews in Kenya, included in the food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful banned insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, can tuna and even the bread bar or chicle were fitted with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon shoot was the most "nutrient" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk generated by these "polluterine cocktails" for the consumer "probably is underestimated," says the study.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
